<!--DOCTYPE para SYSTEM "file:/usr/share/sgml/db42xml/docbookx.dtd"--><ns1714:para xmlns:ns1714="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.platforms.linux.fileSystem.fileSystemStandard.introParagraph">

  To make it easier for people to move accross different distributions, a file system
  standard has been introduced which
  <ns1715:itemizedlist xmlns:ns1715="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    <ns1716:listitem xmlns:ns1716="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns1717:para xmlns:ns1717="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      specifies a minimimal directory hierarchy which should exist on any Linux distribution,
    </ns1717:para></ns1716:listitem>
    <ns1718:listitem xmlns:ns1718="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns1719:para xmlns:ns1719="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      as well as what files these standard directories contain.  
    </ns1719:para></ns1718:listitem>
  </ns1715:itemizedlist>
  This standard file system is part of the Linux base project and has been agreed upon 
  by virtually Linux distributors. It is meant to be a standard for all Unix-based
  systems. The complete standard specification can be downloaded
  from <ns1720:ulink xmlns:ns1720="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" url="http://www.pathname.com/fhs">http://www.pathname.com/fhs</ns1720:ulink>.
</ns1714:para>